	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64604889"><p><em>There are currently 43 companies that are researching fusion through private investment.</em></p><p>OK I'll bite. How many of them are (a) operating without government grants, (b) are producing actual hardware (c) at a scale likely to succeed and (d) not built on the research funded bu the government?</p><p><em>The first fission energy plants (not used for bombs) were commercial and built from nothing to full production in about 6 years.</em></p><p>Firstly, and most importantly, this is not true. The first nuclear power reactor was for a nuclear submarine. The first one built for electrical grid power was by the USSR. The first one built for full commercial operation was Calder Hall built by the British government.</p><p>Even if it were true, the answer is so? Commercial operators got in, doing what they do best after the government put in the basic research legwork. That's how the system works.</p></div>
	</div>

