	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64605313"><p><div class="quote"><p>Bussard pitched several completely different designs over the years. All of them shared one quality: they don't work.</p></div><p>There's been a lot of technologies in the past that didn't work until they did.</p><p>As I recall the issue with Bussard's reactor was it wasn't big enough, then the efficiency would have grown to be net energy positive.  It was a basic squared-cubed problem, energy losses were squared with size while gains were cubed with size.  I recall it was more complex than that but that's a rough idea of the problem.  That's why ITER is as big as it is, they can't prove the engineering with something smaller.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64605313">

